# Prototype Standards

Apply these standards by default when working on this prototype. Be flexible when the current codebase or user request requires it, but call out any important deviation clearly.

## Design System Compliance

- When building new UI, first look for existing design-system patterns for typography, color, spacing, layout, buttons, controls, cards, and states.
- Prefer existing tokens, CSS variables, shared components, and local conventions over hard-coded values or one-off styling.
- If any hard-coded value or custom interaction is necessary, explicitly flag it to the user with the reason and where it was used.

## Build and Runtime QA

- Every time the portfolio is changed (new feature, edit, refactor, content update, or bug fix), treat QA as part of the task before finalizing.
- After implementation, run relevant checks available in the project (build, lint, type, and app/dev checks) when practical.
- Verify the portfolio is up and accessible after changes (for example, local app responds and key routes still load).
- Confirm there are no new runtime/build errors or obvious console-breaking issues introduced by the change.
- Relaunch or re-verify after fixes, then summarize what was checked and any remaining risks.

## Interaction Consistency

- Match interactions to the closest relevant existing page or flow, especially loading states, scrolling behavior, transitions, hover/focus states, and navigation patterns.
- For new articles or content pages, keep loading and scrolling behavior consistent with existing article/content experiences.
- If consistency is not possible because the existing pattern is missing, conflicting, or technically constrained, explain the chosen fallback.

## Project And Article Imagery

- On project detail pages and article detail pages, use a 12px radius for content image frames, content images, and article hero images.
- This radius standard is scoped to project and article pages only; homepage cards, about-page imagery, and other page types remain flexible unless a specific design requires otherwise.
